{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473219"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2039"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2039"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.1,0.32,0.24,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109675"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2039"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92078"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"304"},{"type":"tags","id":"1259"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2101"},{"type":"tags","id":"12762"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46292"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109675"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old Indigenous girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parents, who are concerned about her intermittent limp. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her left hip shows reduced abduction, but her leg lengths are equal. She has mild metatarsus adductus. A review of her birth notes reveals unequal gluteal folds and a \u0027clicky\u0027 left hip. Her parents report she began walking at 18 months. A hip X-ray performed today shows findings consistent with significant acetabular dysplasia due to developmental dysplasia of the hip, with an acetabular index of 43 degrees. The hip is still enlocated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hip spica cast","Dennis-Browne brace","Open reduction","Pelvic osteotomy","Pavlik harness"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a three-year-old girl with developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH) that was likely present from birth but not adequately addressed. The most appropriate management at this stage is a \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvic osteotomy\u003C/strong\u003E. This surgical procedure is indicated for isolated acetabular dysplasia with a stable hip in older children, as it addresses the lack of femoral head coverage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehip spica cast\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used following closed or open reduction in younger infants (6-18 months) with DDH. It is not the primary treatment for an older child with a stable but dysplastic hip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EDennis-Browne brace\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EPavlik harness\u003C/strong\u003E are splinting techniques used for infants diagnosed with DDH in the first six months of life. They are not appropriate for a three-year-old child with established acetabular dysplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen reduction\u003C/strong\u003E is typically performed when closed reduction fails or in older infants (\u0026gt;2 yrs). However, in this case, the hip is still enlocated (in place), so reduction is not necessary. The problem here is the shape of the acetabulum, not the position of the femoral head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is worth noting that DDH represents a spectrum of hip joint dysfunction, including neonatal instability, acetabular dysplasia, hip subluxation, and true dislocation. Early diagnosis is crucial, as treatment becomes more complex with age. Clinical screening, including assessment of hip abduction (the most important clinical sign), should be performed as part of routine neonatal examinations. DDH, if left untreated, can lead to altered hip biomechanics and early osteoarthritis, making it a common cause of total hip replacement in young adults.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Developmental dysplasia of the hip, when recognised early, can usually be managed with splinting techniques.","Isolated acetabular dysplasia with a stable hip in older children often requires pelvic osteotomy to address inadequate femoral head coverage.","Clinical screening for developmental dysplasia of the hip should include assessment of hip abduction, which is the most important clinical sign."],"references":["Vaquero-Picado A, Gonz\u00e1lez-Mor\u00e1n G, Garay EG, Moraleda L. Developmental dysplasia of the hip: update of management. EFORT Open Rev. 2019;4(9):548-56."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92078"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2039"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92078"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-24T16:48:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-24T16:49:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2039"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109675"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.